</p></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><div data-section-id="pf-920c" data-pf-type="Section" class="sc-dxcExB gjNMyZ pf-106_ pf-color-scheme-1 pf-lg-hide pf-md-hide pf-sm-hide"><div style="--cw:1170px" class="sc-kqGpvY OSjcf"><div class="sc-dhKdPU hjOBND pf-107_ pf-r pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-lnPyOc gUmbDa pf-108_"><div class="sc-dhKdPU hjOBND pf-109_ pf-r pf-c-cm pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-lnPyOc gUmbDa pf-110_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-brPMkR cnEYUf pf-111_ pf-heading-1-h3">The vision - What 'systems, not structures' promised
</h3><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Transforming_NI_health_and_social_care_Systems_not_structures_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_ed2b5ce1-6808-4c49-9719-85b2107ea223.jpg?v=1728917309" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Transforming_NI_health_and_social_care_Systems_not_structures_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_ed2b5ce1-6808-4c49-9719-85b2107ea223.jpg?v=1728917309 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Transforming_NI_health_and_social_care_Systems_not_structures_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_ed2b5ce1-6808-4c49-9719-85b2107ea223_1500x.jpg?v=1728917309 1280w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Transforming_NI_health_and_social_care_Systems_not_structures_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_ed2b5ce1-6808-4c49-9719-85b2107ea223_1000x.jpg?v=1728917309 768w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Transforming_NI_health_and_social_care_Systems_not_structures_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_ed2b5ce1-6808-4c49-9719-85b2107ea223_500x.jpg?v=1728917309 320w" width="1820" height="1213" alt="Transforming NI health and social care: Systems, not structures - Dr Richard Dune -" title="Transforming NI health and social care: Systems, not structures - Dr Richard Dune -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-gdyfxU iluFjz pf-113_ pf-image-1"/><p class="sc-iMWBWc laPXAE pf-114_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">Image by fauziEv8 via Envato Elements</p><p class="sc-iMWBWc laPXAE pf-116_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">When the report was released, it painted a dire picture: Northern Ireland’s health system was unsustainable, overly reliant on acute hospital care, and unable to meet the growing demand driven by an ageing population and rising health inequalities. The goal was clear: shift resources toward community and primary care, improve preventative healthcare and address the stark health inequalities across the region.<br><br>The plan's core was the development of Accountable Care Systems (ACS), which would foster integrated, patient-centred care across community, primary, and secondary health services. The report also introduced the Triple Aim framework, which focused on improving patient care, enhancing population health, and reducing per capita healthcare costs.
<br>
</p></div></div></div><div class="sc-dhKdPU hjOBND pf-118_ pf-r pf-c-cm pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-lnPyOc gUmbDa pf-119_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-brPMkR cnEYUf pf-120_ pf-heading-1-h3">Progress or paralysis? The reality from 2016 to 2024
</h3><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Systems_over_structures_A_new_approach_to_NI_health_and_social_care_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_0330de71-42df-42d9-9671-ed33d3e2d36a.jpg?v=1728917309" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Systems_over_structures_A_new_approach_to_NI_health_and_social_care_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_0330de71-42df-42d9-9671-ed33d3e2d36a.jpg?v=1728917309 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Systems_over_structures_A_new_approach_to_NI_health_and_social_care_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_0330de71-42df-42d9-9671-ed33d3e2d36a_1500x.jpg?v=1728917309 1280w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Systems_over_structures_A_new_approach_to_NI_health_and_social_care_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_0330de71-42df-42d9-9671-ed33d3e2d36a_1000x.jpg?v=1728917309 768w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Systems_over_structures_A_new_approach_to_NI_health_and_social_care_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_0330de71-42df-42d9-9671-ed33d3e2d36a_500x.jpg?v=1728917309 320w" width="1766" height="1179" alt="Systems over structures: A new approach to NI health and social care - Dr Richard Dune -" title="Systems over structures: A new approach to NI health and social care - Dr Richard Dune -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-gdyfxU iluFjz pf-122_ pf-image-1"/><p class="sc-iMWBWc laPXAE pf-123_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">Image by LightFieldStudios via Envato Elements</p><p class="sc-iMWBWc laPXAE pf-125_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">Despite the promising vision, the transformation has been painfully slow. Political instability, including the collapse of the Stormont Executive, left a leadership vacuum just when decisive action was most needed. Without sustained political commitment, the healthcare reform agenda stalled.
<br><br>Northern Ireland has seen some progress in implementing the recommendations. Establishing surgical hubs to tackle waiting lists is a notable success, and Integrated Care Partnerships (ICPs) and GP Federations have been rolled out in parts of the region. However, these successes have been overshadowed by budgetary constraints and the pressures of short-term crisis management, particularly following the COVID-19 pandemic.<br><br>The <i>pandemic</i> significantly affected healthcare reform efforts, diverting resources to emergency response. Recovery from the pandemic has further strained an already overstretched system, increasing waiting lists and demand on emergency care services.
</p></div></div></div><div class="sc-dhKdPU hjOBND pf-127_ pf-r pf-c-cm pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-lnPyOc gUmbDa pf-128_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-brPMkR cnEYUf pf-129_ pf-heading-1-h3">Workforce challenges and healthcare inequalities
</h3><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Shaping_the_future_Changing_NI_health_and_social_care_systems_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_ecb77997-a72a-4915-bd99-05355c5874cc.jpg?v=1728917309" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Shaping_the_future_Changing_NI_health_and_social_care_systems_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_ecb77997-a72a-4915-bd99-05355c5874cc.jpg?v=1728917309 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Shaping_the_future_Changing_NI_health_and_social_care_systems_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_ecb77997-a72a-4915-bd99-05355c5874cc_1500x.jpg?v=1728917309 1280w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Shaping_the_future_Changing_NI_health_and_social_care_systems_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_ecb77997-a72a-4915-bd99-05355c5874cc_1000x.jpg?v=1728917309 768w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Shaping_the_future_Changing_NI_health_and_social_care_systems_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_ecb77997-a72a-4915-bd99-05355c5874cc_500x.jpg?v=1728917309 320w" width="1766" height="1179" alt="Shaping the future: Changing NI health and social care systems - Dr Richard Dune -" title="Shaping the future: Changing NI health and social care systems - Dr Richard Dune -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-gdyfxU iluFjz pf-131_ pf-image-1"/><p class="sc-iMWBWc laPXAE pf-132_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">Image by YuriArcursPeopleimages via Envato Elements</p><p class="sc-iMWBWc laPXAE pf-134_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">A critical issue raised in the 2016 report was the workforce crisis - a problem that still persists. The system's reliance on locum and agency staff has become a costly crutch, with workforce shortages leading to <a href="https://www.mandatorytraining.co.uk/blogs/dr-richard-dune/employee-burnout-the-hidden-epidemic-in-health-and-social-care-sector" target="_blank"><em><span style="color: rgb(74, 144, 226);">burnout and poor staff morale</span></em></a>. The lack of long-term workforce planning has undermined efforts toward a sustainable, patient-centred care model.<br><br>Health inequalities also remain a significant issue, with outcomes in deprived areas continuing to lag behind more affluent regions. The vision of bringing care closer to communities through GP-led services has been stifled by funding cuts and the closure of GP practices, further widening the gap in healthcare access across the region.
<br>
</p></div></div></div><div class="sc-dhKdPU hjOBND pf-136_ pf-r pf-c-cm pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-lnPyOc gUmbDa pf-137_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-brPMkR cnEYUf pf-138_ pf-heading-1-h3">Resistance to change - Centralisation and public sentiment
</h3><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Rethinking_NI_health_and_social_care_Why_systems_matter_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_d2627c8a-7b53-4357-bfa2-7d81c2810f02.jpg?v=1728917309" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Rethinking_NI_health_and_social_care_Why_systems_matter_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_d2627c8a-7b53-4357-bfa2-7d81c2810f02.jpg?v=1728917309 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Rethinking_NI_health_and_social_care_Why_systems_matter_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_d2627c8a-7b53-4357-bfa2-7d81c2810f02_1500x.jpg?v=1728917309 1280w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Rethinking_NI_health_and_social_care_Why_systems_matter_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_d2627c8a-7b53-4357-bfa2-7d81c2810f02_1000x.jpg?v=1728917309 768w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Rethinking_NI_health_and_social_care_Why_systems_matter_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_d2627c8a-7b53-4357-bfa2-7d81c2810f02_500x.jpg?v=1728917309 320w" width="1904" height="1270" alt="Rethinking NI health and social care: Why systems matter - Dr Richard Dune -" title="Rethinking NI health and social care: Why systems matter - Dr Richard Dune -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-gdyfxU iluFjz pf-140_ pf-image-1"/><p class="sc-iMWBWc laPXAE pf-141_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">Image by YuriArcursPeopleimages via Envato Elements</p><p class="sc-iMWBWc laPXAE pf-143_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">Another core recommendation of the report was the rationalisation of hospital services - consolidating specialised care to create centres of excellence while shifting non-urgent services to community settings. Although the centralisation of some services has progressed, it has been met with public resistance, particularly in rural areas where patients now face longer journeys for specialist care.<br><br>For political leaders, closing or downgrading hospitals is far from a vote-winner, contributing to the slow pace of reform. The balance between maintaining local services and creating a more efficient, sustainable system remains politically fraught.
<br>
</p></div></div></div><div class="sc-dhKdPU hjOBND pf-145_ pf-r pf-c-cm pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-lnPyOc gUmbDa pf-146_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-brPMkR cnEYUf pf-147_ pf-heading-1-h3">Bengoa’s 2024 revisit - A reality check
</h3><img alt="Systems vs. structures Redefining NI health and social care - Dr Richard Dune -.jpg__PID:90ae0c97-f9ec-4b44-91b8-16be62177f53" src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Systems_vs._structures_Redefining_NI_health_and_social_care_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_c432e0a4-4133-42b8-8f78-1c21cc456974.jpg?v=1729063725" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Systems_vs._structures_Redefining_NI_health_and_social_care_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_c432e0a4-4133-42b8-8f78-1c21cc456974.jpg?v=1729063725&width=550 550w,https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Systems_vs._structures_Redefining_NI_health_and_social_care_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_c432e0a4-4133-42b8-8f78-1c21cc456974.jpg?v=1729063725&width=768 768w,https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Systems_vs._structures_Redefining_NI_health_and_social_care_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_c432e0a4-4133-42b8-8f78-1c21cc456974.jpg?v=1729063725&width=1024 1024w,https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Systems_vs._structures_Redefining_NI_health_and_social_care_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_c432e0a4-4133-42b8-8f78-1c21cc456974.jpg?v=1729063725&width=1200 1200w,https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Systems_vs._structures_Redefining_NI_health_and_social_care_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_c432e0a4-4133-42b8-8f78-1c21cc456974.jpg?v=1729063725&width=1400 1400w,https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Systems_vs._structures_Redefining_NI_health_and_social_care_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_c432e0a4-4133-42b8-8f78-1c21cc456974.jpg?v=1729063725&width=1600 1600w,https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Systems_vs._structures_Redefining_NI_health_and_social_care_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_c432e0a4-4133-42b8-8f78-1c21cc456974.jpg?v=1729063725&width=1800 1800w,https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Systems_vs._structures_Redefining_NI_health_and_social_care_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_c432e0a4-4133-42b8-8f78-1c21cc456974.jpg?v=1729063725&width=1920 1920w,https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Systems_vs._structures_Redefining_NI_health_and_social_care_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_c432e0a4-4133-42b8-8f78-1c21cc456974.jpg?v=1729063725&width=2048 2048w" fetchPriority="auto" decoding="async" loading="lazy" width="1748" height="1009" sizes="75vw" data-pf-type="Image4" class="sc-bDoQz fHJoao pf-149_ pf-image-1" store="[object Object]"/><p class="sc-iMWBWc laPXAE pf-150_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">Image by iLixe48 via Envato Elements</p><p class="sc-iMWBWc laPXAE pf-152_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">In 2024, Professor Bengoa returned to Northern Ireland to assess the progress made since his 2016 report. His conclusion was sobering. While there have been some advancements, major struggles remain in balancing the immediate pressures on the health system with long-term reform needs.
<br><br>Mike Nesbitt, Northern Ireland’s Health Minister, has acknowledged the need for radical decisions but faces the same budgetary and political constraints that have dogged the system for years. Nesbitt’s promise to be the man who makes the "difficult calls" echoes the urgency of the moment - but the window for meaningful action is closing.
</p></div></div></div><div class="sc-dhKdPU hjOBND pf-154_ pf-r pf-c-cm pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-lnPyOc gUmbDa pf-155_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-brPMkR cnEYUf pf-156_ pf-heading-1-h3">The road ahead - Time for bold decisions
</h3><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Building_better_systems_for_NI_health_and_social_care_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_646d7aa9-0765-4742-9b3e-e52ab6ac48fb.jpg?v=1728917309" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Building_better_systems_for_NI_health_and_social_care_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_646d7aa9-0765-4742-9b3e-e52ab6ac48fb.jpg?v=1728917309 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Building_better_systems_for_NI_health_and_social_care_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_646d7aa9-0765-4742-9b3e-e52ab6ac48fb_1000x.jpg?v=1728917309 768w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Building_better_systems_for_NI_health_and_social_care_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_646d7aa9-0765-4742-9b3e-e52ab6ac48fb_500x.jpg?v=1728917309 320w" width="1183" height="783" alt="Building better systems for NI health and social care - Dr Richard Dune -" title="Building better systems for NI health and social care - Dr Richard Dune -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-gdyfxU iluFjz pf-158_ pf-image-1"/><p class="sc-iMWBWc laPXAE pf-159_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">Image by iLixe48 via Envato Elements</p><p class="sc-iMWBWc laPXAE pf-161_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">Eight years after the publication of Systems, Not Structures, Northern Ireland’s health and social care system still faces the same crossroads. Without bold leadership and sustained financial investment, the vision laid out in 2016 will remain a distant aspiration rather than a reality. The healthcare system, its workforce, and most importantly, its patients cannot afford further delays.<br><br>The next steps are clear: prioritise <a href="https://www.mandatorytraining.co.uk/blogs/dr-richard-dune/workforce-development-in-the-uk-s-health-and-social-care-sector" target="_blank"><em><span style="color: rgb(74, 144, 226);">workforce development, scale up successful innovations</span></em></a>, and commit to the long-term transformation needed to deliver patient-centred care. The political will to make difficult decisions and sustained financial backing will be crucial to moving from slow progress to true reform.
